Social Media Do’s and Don’ts for College Students
Do’s

Keep your profiles updated
Make sure your LinkedIn and GitHub profiles are complete from the beginning. Even basic details like your course, college, 
and what you’re learning are enough to create a good impression.

Think before you post
Before sharing anything, consider whether you’d be comfortable if a professor or recruiter saw it. If you’re unsure, it’s 
better not to post.

Use strong account security
Avoid using the same password everywhere. Using a password manager and enabling two-factor authentication (2FA) can help 
protect your accounts.

Verify information before sharing
If something seems doubtful or too extreme, take a moment to check it. Sharing incorrect information can affect your 
credibility.

Check your privacy settings regularly
Social media settings can change, so it’s a good idea to review them once in a while to ensure your data is safe.

Log out from shared devices
Always log out when using public or someone else’s device to avoid misuse of your accounts.

Don’ts

Don’t share personal information
Avoid posting sensitive details like phone numbers, addresses, or ID documents, as they can be misused.

Don’t share academic content
Posting assignment answers or exam-related material can lead to academic issues and should be avoided.

Avoid online arguments
Engaging in public arguments rarely leads to anything positive, so it’s better to ignore and move on.

Don’t click suspicious links
Links from unknown sources can be harmful, even if they look genuine.

Don’t share your live location
Posting your location while you are still there can be unsafe. It’s better to share it later.
